{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496442","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496442"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:47:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:47:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1363"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1363","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1363"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.19,0.05,0.65,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1363"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81709"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1363","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1363"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1363"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67009"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"38"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"721"},{"type":"tags","id":"1804"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4991"},{"type":"tags","id":"10927"},{"type":"tags","id":"11622"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1871"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1873"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43979"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44982"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81709","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/81709"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents to a visiting doctor at a remote Indigenous community clinic for a routine health check. She works for an aid organisation. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She reports feeling well with no specific concerns. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Ocular examination reveals multiple discrete circular follicles on the subtarsal conjunctiva (Image). Extra-ocular movements are normal and her corrected visual acuity is 6/6 bilaterally.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Chalazion","Blepharitis","Hyphema","Trachoma","Dacryocystitis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with characteristic findings of early trachoma, with follicular inflammation visible on the subtarsal conjunctiva. \u003Cstrong\u003ETrachoma\u003C/strong\u003E is caused by \u003Cem\u003EChlamydia trachomatis\u003C/em\u003E serotypes A, B, Ba and C, distinct from the sexually transmitted strains (serotypes D to K). The former can be sight-threatening, whereas the latter is generally benign and self-limiting. It remains endemic in remote Aboriginal communities and regions of socioeconomic disadvantage globally.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChalazion\u003C/strong\u003E presents as a localised painless swelling on the upper eyelid due to blocked meibomian glands. It appears as a firm, round nodule within the tarsal plate and may cause mechanical ptosis if large enough. The examination findings in this case do not match this presentation, as chalazions do not cause follicular changes of the conjunctiva.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlepharitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes bilateral lid erythema, flaking, and itching. It is a chronic inflammatory condition affecting the eyelid margins, often associated with seborrhoeic dermatitis or staphylococcal infection. The absence of these symptoms and the presence of subtarsal follicles make this diagnosis unlikely. Blepharitis does not cause follicular changes of the conjunctiva.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyphema\u003C/strong\u003E refers to bleeding in the anterior chamber, typically following trauma or surgery. This would be visible as a blood level in the anterior chamber, which is not present in this case. Hyphema is often associated with pain, photophobia, and decreased vision, none of which are present in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDacryocystitis\u003C/strong\u003E presents as a tender, fluctuant mass near the medial canthus due to lacrimal sac infection. It is typically unilateral and associated with pain, erythema, and purulent discharge. The examination findings are not consistent with this diagnosis, as dacryocystitis does not cause follicular changes of the conjunctiva.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEarly trachoma is often asymptomatic and detected during routine screening. Without treatment, repeated infections can lead to scarring, entropion (inward-turning eyelids), and eventually blindness from corneal damage. Transmission occurs through direct contact with ocular and nasal secretions, with flies serving as mechanical vectors. The World Health Organization\u0027s SAFE strategy (Surgery for advanced disease, Antibiotics, Facial cleanliness, and Environmental improvement) forms the cornerstone of trachoma control programs.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Trachoma is characterized by follicular inflammation of the tarsal conjunctiva and is caused by Chlamydia trachomatis serotypes A, B, Ba and C.","Trachoma is often asymptomatic in early stages and is commonly detected during routine screening in endemic areas.","Trachoma remains endemic in remote Aboriginal communities and regions of socioeconomic disadvantage globally."],"references":["Bowman RJC, Faal H, Myatt M, et al. Longitudinal study of trachomatous trichiasis in the Gambia. Br J Ophthalmol. 2002 Mar;86(3):339-43.","Taylor HR, Burton MJ, Haddad D, West S, Wright H. Trachoma. The Lancet (British edition). 2014 Dec;384(9960):2142\u201352.","Eye emergency manual: an illustrated guide. NSW Agency for Clinical Innovation. 2023. Available from: https://aci.health.nsw.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0013/155011/ACI-Eye-Emergency-Manual.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67009"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1363"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18585"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18585","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18585"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/fd244924-6a7d-4c37-8d2c-083cd0035c9a.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/fd244924-6a7d-4c37-8d2c-083cd0035c9a.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":418}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67009","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67009"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-26T20:09:46+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-26T20:11:00+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1363"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81709"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"met